# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
<overview>
<p>The Drake is a Word of Blake orbital control station developed as the command node for the Maginot Line's automated defense network. A substantial modification of the Terran Hegemony's Gatekeeper traffic control stations, it combines the Gatekeeper's proven long-range communications architecture with reinforced armor, upgraded weapons, and sophisticated drone control systems. Introduced in 3071 and manufactured at the O'Neil Yards' Titan Yards section on Terra, each Drake served as the nerve center coordinating a network of Caspar II drones, drone fighters, and ground-based platforms defending a Maginot world. Though modest in size for an orbital platform, the Drake's command and control capabilities made it disproportionately dangerous as the apex node of an integrated layered defense, capable of directing autonomous weapons across a wide orbital envelope while withstanding casual attack from its own defensive armament.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>At 12,000 tons, the Drake is designed around command and control rather than direct combat power. A Large Naval Comm-Scanner Suite provides monitoring and communications capability across several astronomical units, while the Direct Tactical Analysis Control System coordinates up to eighteen Caspar II drones simultaneously, allowing a single Drake to orchestrate fire from slaved drone assets, drone fighters, and ground-based SDS platforms in a layered integrated response.</p><p>For direct combat, the Drake mounts twenty-three weapon bays across six arcs. Each arc carries paired extended-range large lasers, dual multi-missile launchers with Artemis IV guidance, and a bank of medium pulse lasers providing close-range coverage. The nose arc adds a sub-capital missile launcher for strikes against larger vessels. Anti-missile systems in the nose and aft arcs defend against incoming salvos, while screen launchers in three arcs provide a final deterrent against closing attackers.</p><p>Supporting operations, the Drake carries an unpressurized naval repair bay rated for vessels up to 5,000 tons, four small craft, and approximately 3,700 tons of cargo stores. A single 600-meter grav deck supports a crew of 115, along with twelve battle armor troopers providing internal security. Fifteen lifeboats provide emergency evacuation capacity.</p><p>The Drake's fundamental vulnerability is immobility. Unable to maneuver under fire, it depends entirely on its drone network and defensive armament to hold, and its effectiveness is sharply reduced without its full complement of slaved Caspar IIs.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Drake served exclusively as a Word of Blake asset from its introduction in 3071 through the end of the Jihad. Deployed above worlds designated as part of the Maginot Line defense network, individual Drake stations acted as command nodes around which clusters of Caspar II drones, drone fighters, and ground-based SDS platforms were organized. Each Drake's effectiveness depended heavily on the availability of its associated drone assets - without a full complement of slaved Caspar IIs, a Drake was little more than a moderately armed orbital platform. Coalition assault planners treated Drake neutralization as a tactical prerequisite for any viable landing operation on Maginot worlds, prioritizing their elimination before committing assault forces. After the Jihad's conclusion, surviving examples came under Republic of the Sphere control along with the broader Terra system infrastructure, though operational details from the Dark Age period remain sparse.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Gatekeeper traffic control stations were a Terran Hegemony design that had served as orbital administrative platforms across hundreds of inhabited systems for generations. After the Hegemony's fall, surviving Gatekeepers continued operating largely undisturbed, permanent fixtures of the Inner Sphere's space traffic infrastructure and generally ignored by the Successor States.</p><p>When Precentor Martial Cameron St. Jamais began planning the Maginot Line orbital defense network, these familiar platforms provided an obvious foundation. The Caspar II automated drone program required command nodes capable of coordinating large drone clusters across wide orbital envelopes, and the Gatekeeper's established communications architecture offered a proven starting point. St. Jamais directed the reopening of the Titan Yards section of the O'Neil complex on Terra (the facility that had originally manufactured the Gatekeeper design) and ordered its conversion to produce the heavily modified Drake. The resulting design, entering service in 3071, took the Gatekeeper's frame and communications backbone and transformed it into a dedicated command-and-control platform reinforced for sustained combat operations.</p><p>Drake stations were deployed above Maginot worlds throughout the Jihad, serving as the apex nodes of layered SDS networks that made those worlds extraordinarily costly for Coalition forces to approach. Their drone coordination capability allowed a single station to act as a force multiplier far exceeding what its own weapons suggested, and the Coalition recognized this immediately. Drake stations were designated as high-priority targets in any assault on a defended world, typically assigned to specialized interdiction units before ground operations could begin.</p><p>By the war's end, most Drakes had been destroyed in the intense fighting around Maginot worlds and the final campaigns on Terra itself. The Titan Yards did not survive the conflict, and no new production has been documented since. The few Drakes that survived fell under Republic of the Sphere control along with the broader O'Neil infrastructure, though whether any remain operational through the Dark Age is unknown.</p>
</history>

